\mainmatter
You don't need to understand these things to use spider cipher.

You do need to trust that the cipher is secure and this is the
background to understand why. The arguments here are based on proofs,
sometimes assisted by a computer program.

A person with a college background in mathematics or theoretical
computer science should be able to understand and validate the ideas
here.

\hypertarget{facts}{%
\chapter{Facts}\label{facts}}

Carefully stated facts are usually like
\begin{quote}
If these assumptions are true, then these ideas are true.    
\end{quote}

Facts might seem simple, but they are not. It is not possible to know
everything, and we live in a world of deception, misunderstandings, and
incomplete information. So a good practical goal is to be wise about
facts.

The most careful curators of facts are mathematicians. What is nice
about mathematics is, even if you do not like or trust or know the
people who have built up a body of facts, they can be verified by anyone
with the background to understand the arguments, called proofs, and they
will be facts in any case.

Of course, mathematicians are fallible: what are thought of as
proofs are sometimes later determined to be incorrect. But the public
review of facts and their proofs makes the core body of facts, those
that have been used for decades or even centuries, very likely to be
true.

For some proofs, following repetitive patterns is impossibly hard for
humans. Using computer programs can facilitate showing that certain facts are
true. Running a program means trusting that the program is written
correctly and that it is running on a correctly working computer. Modern
computers are very complex, as are modern programming languages. But,
similar to the proofs of mathematicians, these programs can be reviewed
by qualified computer scientists, and run repeatedly on multiple
computers to validate that they are correct.

In order to validate a set of facts, it is helpful that the things that
those facts depend on are reasonably limited. We keep the mathematical
background limited to ideas that have a large body of work that validate
them, and would be accessible to a mathematician or theoretical computer
scientist with a good undergraduate background in the field.

Similarly, the programs are written in C because this is an old and
common programming language which can be used on many kinds of
computers.

\hypertarget{numbers}{%
\chapter{Numbers}\label{numbers}}

We write numbers in base 10 almost always, but we will write in another
base occasionally and subscript by the base when a distinction is
needed. So \(32_{10} = 100000_{2}\). Because the comma is important in
other notation and has different meanings in different languages, we use
\_ (underbar) as a digit grouping mark, which is the convention in
several computer languages, so
\begin{equation*}
65\_ 536.062\_ 500_{10}\,,
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
1\_ 0000\_ 0000\_ 0000\_ 0000.0001_{2}\,,
\end{equation*}
and
\begin{equation*}
1\_ 00\_ 00.1_{16}
\end{equation*}
are all ways to write the same number.

For base 16, a common choice for computers, the digit symbols are extended with \(\mathrm{a}\) through \(\mathrm{f}\) to give the 16 needed possibilities, so
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{bee.4}_{16}=11\times 16^2
+14 \times 16^1
+14 \times 16^0
+4 \times 16^{-1} = 3\_ 054.25_{10}\,.
\end{equation*}

\hypertarget{integers}{%
\section{Integers}\label{integers}}

Integer numbers are all the counting numbers, including 0, and
their negatives. So these include \(0\), \(7\), \(- 88\) and
\begin{equation*}
10!=10 \times 9 \times 8 \times \cdots \times 3 \times 2 \times 1 = 3\_ 628\_ 800
\end{equation*}
but not \(12.345\) nor \(\pi = 3.14159...\). Integers can be thought of as labels of posts along a perfectly regular fence going on forever in either direction.

\hypertarget{reals}{%
\section{Reals}\label{reals}}

Real numbers are the points on the number line and represent all
distances, including \(0\), and their negatives. So these include all
the integers, but also \(12.345\) and \(\pi = 3.14159...\) These can be thought of as positions along a perfectly straight wire strung along the posts of the integers.

\hypertarget{lists}{%
\chapter{Lists}\label{lists}}

Lists are collections of items where there is an initial one, a next one, etc., and a last one. For example \([]\),
\([\text{`apple'}]\), and \([ \text{`apple'}, \text{`banana'}]\) are
lists with 0, 1, and 2 items. Generally a list of \(n\) items we write
as \([ l(0),l(1),...,l(n - 1)]\). So, for
\(l = [\text{`apple'},\text{`banana'}]\), \(l(0) = \text{`apple'}\) and
\(l(1) = \text{`banana'}\). We write \(\# l\) for the number of items in the
list, so, for this example, \(\# l = 2\).

Order matters and repetition is allowed in lists, so
\(F_8 = [ 0,1,1,2,3,5,8,13]\) is a perfectly good list of length
\(\# F_8 = 8\), where \(F_8(1) = 1\) and \(F_8(2) = 1\).

We use \(0\)-based indexing in these notes. This is the convention for
many common programming languages, and so makes translating ideas into
code simpler.

\hypertarget{strings}{%
\chapter{Strings}\label{strings}}

Strings are a shorthand for a list of code points, typically unicode (an
international standard covering most written languages), so
\(\text{`apple'} = [ 97,112,112,108,101]\), because latin `a' is unicode codepoint 97, etc. So in the lists
example, \(l = [\text{`apple'},\text{`banana'}]\) is really a list of
lists:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
l &= [\text{`apple'}, \text{`banana'}] \\
  &= [[97,112,112,108,101], [98,97,109,97,109,97]]
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

\hypertarget{sets}{%
\chapter{Sets}\label{sets}}

Sets are collections of items, and all that matters about a set is if
something is in it, or not. Here are some basic notations:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  We use big letters for sets like \(S\) or \(T\), or
  \(\{ \text{description} \}\), or just what is in the set
  in curly braces: 
  \begin{equation*}
V = \{ \text{vowels} \} = \{ \text{`a'},\text{`e'},\text{`i'},\text{`o'},\text{`u'},\text{`y'} \}\,.      
  \end{equation*}
\item
  Order and duplication do not matter:
\begin{equation*}
\{ \text{`a'},\text{`b'}\} = \{ \text{`b'},\text{`a'}\} = \{ \text{`a'},\text{`a'},\text{`a'},\text{`b'},\text{`b'}\} \,.
\end{equation*}
\item
  Counting the elements in \(S\) we write as \(\# S\), so:
\begin{equation*}
\# \{ \text{`a'},\text{`b'}\} = \# \{ \text{`b'},\text{`a'}\} = \# \{ \text{`a'},\text{`a'},\text{`a'},\text{`b'},\text{`b'}\} = 2\,.
\end{equation*}
\item
  The empty set \(\Theta=\{\}\) contains nothing: \( \# \Theta = 0 \).
\item
  The largest set depends on the problem, but is the set that contains
  all the elements of concern for a problem. This is usually called the
  universal set or just \(U\).
\item
  A subset is a set entirely within another: \(A \subseteq B\) if all
  the elements of \(A\) are in \(B\). It is called a proper subset
  \(A \subset B\) if there is something in \(B\) that is not in \(A\).
  So \(B\) is the only subset of \(B\) that is not a proper subset.
\item
  ``\(e\ \epsilon\ S\)'', ``\(e\) in \(S\)'', ``\(e:S\)'', and ``\(e\)
  is an element of \(S\)'' all mean the same thing.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{formal-sets}{%
\section{Formal Sets}\label{formal-sets}}
The most formal version of describing a set looks like:
\begin{equation*}
X = \{ x : U \ \&\  \text{additional properties of \(x\)}\}
\end{equation*}
Think that all the elements of \(X\) are in \(U\), but have additional constraints that may eliminate some or all of them. You can read this as ``\(X\) is all the elements \(x\) of \(U\) with the given properties''. Here are a few useful sets for us:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \(Z = \{ \text{integers} \} = \{..., - 3, - 2, - 1,0,1,2,3,...\}\). The
  regular counting numbers, including zero and negative values are the integers; \( \# Z = \infty \). The truly formal definition of this is not useful here.
\item
  \(R = \{ \text{reals} \}\). All distances, including zero and negative distances.  This includes all the integers, but also things like \(-\frac{1}{3}\), \(\sqrt{2}\) and \(\pi \approx 3.14\ldots \). Again, the formal definition of this is not useful here. 
\item
  For any integer \(n\) that is greater than or equal to \(0\),
  \begin{equation*}
  Z_{n} = \{0,1,2,\ldots,n - 1\} \,.  
  \end{equation*}
  \(\# Z_{n} = n\). For example \(Z_{3} = \{ 0,1,2\}\) and \(\#Z_3 = 3 \).
\item
  For any integer \(n\) that is greater than or equal to \(0\),
  \begin{equation*}
  S_{n} = \{ \text{all arrangements of \(Z_{n}\)}\} \,.
  \end{equation*}
  The arrangements come from \(n\) choices for the first element, then \( n - 1\) choices for the second, etc., so:
  \begin{equation*}
\#S_n = n! = (n) \times (n-1) \times (n-2) \times \ldots \times (1)\,.
  \end{equation*}
  For example,
  \begin{equation*}
S_{3} = \{[ 0,1,2],[ 0,2,1],[ 1,0,2],[ 1,2,0],[ 2,0,1],[ 2,1,0]\}
  \end{equation*}
  and
  \begin{equation*}
  \# S_3 = 3! = 3 \times 2 \times 1 = 6 \,.
  \end{equation*}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{venn-diagram}{%
\section{Venn Diagram}\label{venn-diagram}}

The Venn Diagram (figure~\ref{fig:venn}) is the most important diagram for sets.
\begin{figure}
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{build/figures/venn.pdf}
\caption{Venn diagram for two generic sets \(A\) and \(B\)}
\label{fig:venn}
\end{figure}

The two circles represent two sets \(A\) and \(B\) as two subsets of
some universal set \(U\) which is the rectangle.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Intersection (like the intersection of two roads). The elements in
  both \(A\) and \(B\) is the rugby ball between them. These elements
  are in the i\(\cap\)tersection of \(A\) with \(B\), and is written
  \(A \cap B\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Union (like the union of marriage). The elements in either \(A\) or
  \(B\) is the peanut with both of them. These elements are in the
  \(\cup\)nion of \(A\) with \(B\), and is written \(A \cup B\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Notice that the elements in the union (peanut) double counts the
  elements in the intersection (rugby ball), so
  \(\#(A \cup B) = (\# A) + (\# B) - \#(A \cap B)\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Set subtraction \(A - B\) is all the elements of \(A\) that are not in
  \(B\) (or \(A\) except the rugby ball).
  \(\#(A - B) = \# A - \#(A \cap B)\).
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{partition}{%
\section{Partition}\label{partition}}

Suppose some set \(S\) can be written as a union of \(N\) other sets:
\(S = A_{0} \cup A_{1} \cup A_{2} \cup \cdot \cdot \cdot \cup A_{N - 1}\),
and that the sets have nothing in common: \(A_{i} \cap A_{j} = \Theta\)
whenever \(i \neq j\). Then we say the set of subsets
\(\{ A_{0},A_{1},A_{2},...,A_{N - 1}\}\) is a partition of \(S\). If you
made a Venn diagram like above for a partition, each subset \(A_{i}\)
would ``paint'' a part of \(S\) in a way that, in total, all of \(S\) is
painted, and no paint overlaps (all the rugby balls are empty). Since
all the rugby balls are empty, there is no double counting and so
\(\# S = (\# A_{0}) + (\# A_{1}) + (\# A_{2}) + \cdot \cdot \cdot + (\# A_{N - 1})\).

\hypertarget{modular-arithmetic}{%
\chapter{Modular Arithmetic}\label{modular-arithmetic}}

It is helpful to define a modified set of arithmetic operations that
restrict the results to \(Z_{n} = \{ 0,1,...n - 1\}\). If normal integer
arithmetic is walking along a fence that runs to the horizon in either
direction, then modular arithmetic is walking around a circular pen with
\(n\) posts labeled \(0\) through \(n - 1\).

\hypertarget{addition}{%
\section{Addition}\label{addition}}

Modulo-\(n\) addition \(x\  \oplus_{n}\ y\) is the same as \(x + y\),
except the result is shifted up or down by multiples of \(n\) until the
result is in the range \(0 \leq x\  \oplus_{n}\ y < n\).

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  For example, \(3\  \oplus_{10}\ 9 = 2\), because \(3 + 9 = 12\), but
  that is above the range \(0 \leq \# < 10\), so it is shifted down
  (once) to \(2\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Using negatives, \(( - 7){\  \oplus}_{10}\ 5 = 8\), because
  \(( - 7) + 5 = - 2\), is below the range \(0 \leq \# < 10\), so it is
  shifted up (once) to \(8\).
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{multiplication}{%
\section{Multiplication}\label{multiplication}}

Like addition, modulo-\(n\) multiplication \(x \otimes_{n}y\) is defined
as normal multiplication, \(x \times y\), except the result is shifted
up or down by multiples of \(n\) until the result is in the range
\(0 \leq x\  \otimes_{n}\ y < n\).

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  For example \(3{\  \otimes}_{10}\ 9 = 7\), because
  \(3 \times 9 = 27\), which can be shifted down to \(7\) by subtracting
  \(20\) which is a multiple of \(10\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Similarly \(( - 3){\  \otimes}_{10}\ 9 = 3\), because \(- 27 + 30\)
  lies in the proper range.
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{subtraction}{%
\section{Subtraction}\label{subtraction}}

Modulo-\(n\) subtraction is defined in terms of addition by
\(x \ominus_{n}y = x \oplus_{n}(n - y)\). In this way \(\ominus_{n}\)
undoes \(\oplus_{n}\) as in \(x \ominus x = x \oplus (n - x) = 0\).

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  For example
  \(3{\  \ominus}_{10}\ 9 = 3\  \oplus_{10}\ (10 - 9) = 3\  \oplus_{10}\ 1\  = \ 4\)
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{division}{%
\section{Division}\label{division}}

Analogous to how subtraction undoes addition, modulo-\(n\) division
\(\oslash_{n}\) is defined to undo modulo-\(n\) multiplication. Thinking
about \(x/y = z\) means \(x = z \times y\), if it is unique, we define
\({x \oslash}_{n}y\) to be the only integer, \(0 \leq z < n\), for which
\(x = z \otimes_{n}y\).

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  For example, \(1 \oslash_{3}2 = 2\), because \(2 \otimes_{3}2 = 1\).
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

Usually the subscript is dropped if the value of \(n\) is understood
from the context. When talking about \(Z_{40}\), \(\oplus\) means
\(\oplus_{40}\).

\hypertarget{relations-and-functions}{%
\chapter{Relations and Functions}\label{relations-and-functions}}

\hypertarget{relation}{%
\section{Relation}\label{relation}}

A relation is a set of connections between two sets of things.

For example,\(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\)
relates the set of letters \(\{\text{`a'},\text{`b'}\}\) to the set of words
\(\{\text{`alpha'},\text{`bravo'}\}\).

Familiar relations use familiar symbols like \(<\) or \(\neq\) instead
of a generic arrow \(\rightarrow\). For example, the less-than relation
in \(Z_{3}\) would be \(\{ 0 < 1,0 < 2,1 < 2\}\)

\hypertarget{inverse-relation}{%
\section{Inverse Relation}\label{inverse-relation}}

If all the arrows are flipped, that is the inverse relation, so
\(\{\text{`alpha'} \rightarrow \text{`a'},\text{`bravo'} \rightarrow \text{`b'}\}\) is the inverse
relation of \(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\). We
superscript by \(- 1\) to indicate an inverse, so

\(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}^{- 1} = \{\text{`alpha'} \rightarrow \text{`a'},\text{`bravo'} \rightarrow \text{`b'}\}\)

Clearly the inverse of the inverse is the original relation.

\hypertarget{function}{%
\section{Function}\label{function}}

Functions are relations where the ``from'' side of the arrow only shows
up once. This means that for any allowed ``from'' or ``begin'' or
``input'', there is an unambiguous ``to'' or ``end'' or ``output''. If
\(x \rightarrow y\) is in some function, then we say the function maps
\(x\) to \(y\).

For example, \(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\) is
a function that maps \(\text{`a'}\) to \(\text{`apple'}\) and \(\text{`b'}\) to \(\text{`bravo'}\).

As a counter-example,
\(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`apple'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\)
is a relation, but not a function, because it maps \(\text{`a'}\) to both
\(\text{`alpha'}\) and \(\text{`apple'}\).

\hypertarget{domain-and-range}{%
\section{Domain and Range}\label{domain-and-range}}

For functions, The ``from/begin/input'' set is called the domain and the
``to/end/output'' set is called the range. So the domain of
\(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\) is
\(\{\text{`a'},\text{`b'}\}\) and the range is \(\{\text{`alpha'},\text{`bravo'}\}\).

We will take a narrow view of the terms domain and range here. For
example, the function

\(\{ 0 \rightarrow 0,1 \rightarrow 2\}\) has domain \(\{ 0,1\}\) and
range \(\{ 0,2\}\). Some would write the domain and range is
\(Z_{3} = \{ 0,1,2\}\) but this is too large in both cases, since \(2\)
is never a ``from'' and \(1\) is never a ``to''.

\hypertarget{named-functions}{%
\section{Named Functions}\label{named-functions}}

Functions can be named, like
\(c = \{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\), and then
write \(c(\text{`a'}) = \text{`alpha'}\) and \(c(\text{`b'}) = \text{`bravo'}\). Notice this
notation would not make sense for relations in general, since for
\(r = \{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`apple'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\),
\(r(\text{`a'})\) could be \(\text{`alpha'}\) or `\(apple'\).

\hypertarget{inverse-function}{%
\section{Inverse Function}\label{inverse-function}}

Inverting (flipping the arrows) on a function will always produce a
relation, and may produce a function. If the inverse of a function is a
function, then that function is called invertible.

Invertible functions are functions that can be backtracked. So, using
the forward function you can unambiguously move from a ``from'' or
``begin'' or ``input'' to a ``to'' or ``end'' or ``output'', and by
using the inverse function, you can also move from any ``to'' or ``end''
or ``output'' unambiguously to a ``from'' or ``begin'' or ``input''.

For example, the inverse of
\(c = \{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`alpha'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`bravo'}\}\) is

\(c^{- 1} = \{\text{`alpha'} \rightarrow \text{`a'},\text{`bravo'} \rightarrow \text{`b'}\}\)

Since this is also a function then \(c\) is an invertible function.

As a counter-example
\(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`x'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`y'},\text{`c'} \rightarrow \text{`x'}\}\) is a
function, but it is not invertible because you cannot unambiguously
backtrack from \(\text{`x'}\). The inverse
\(\{\text{`x'} \rightarrow \text{`a'},\text{`y'} \rightarrow \text{`b'},\text{`x'} \rightarrow \text{`c'}\}\) is a
relation, but not a function.

\hypertarget{list-as-a-function}{%
\section{List as a Function}\label{list-as-a-function}}

We started with describing a list independently from function, but you
can think of a list as a function with the domain (from set) of
\(Z_{n} = \{ 0,1,...,n - 1\}\). The following structure is equivalent:
\(l = [ l(0),l(1),...,l(n - 1)]\) and
\(l = \{ 0 \rightarrow l(0),\ 1 \rightarrow l(1),...,n - 1 \rightarrow l(n - 1)\}\)

For example, the list \([\text{`apple'},\text{`banana'}]\) is equivalent
to the function \(\{ 0 \rightarrow \text{`apple'},1 \rightarrow \text{`banana'}\}.\)

Notice \(\# l\) thought of as a list and \(\# l\) thought of as the set
of mappings gives the same result.

\hypertarget{permutation}{%
\section{Permutation}\label{permutation}}

If the domain and range are the same finite set, then an invertible
function is also called a permutation of the domain. For example,
\(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow \text{`b'},\text{`b'} \rightarrow \text{`a'},\text{`c'} \rightarrow \text{`c'}\}\) is a
permutation of \(\{\text{`a'},\text{`b'},\text{`c'}\}\).

Permutations rearrange elements of a set. Since a set of \(\ n\)
elements can be labeled with \(0\) through \(n - 1\), every permutation
is equivalently a permutation of \(Z_{n}\). Labeling
\(\{\text{`a'} \rightarrow 0,\text{`b'} \rightarrow 1,\text{`c'} \rightarrow 2\}\), the
previous example becomes,
\(\{ 0 \rightarrow 1,1 \rightarrow 0,2 \rightarrow 2\}\), or
\([ 1,0,2]\) as a list.

\hypertarget{formulaic-functions}{%
\section{Formulaic Functions}\label{formulaic-functions}}

A convenient all-in-one notation is
\(f:\{ domain\} \rightarrow \{ range\} = \{ x \rightarrow\)
formula\(\}\). Which can be read as ``\(f\) is a function from
\(\{ domain\}\) to \(\{ range\}\) where \(f(x) =\) formula''. For
example,

\(t:\ Z_{n} \rightarrow Z_{n} = \{ x \rightarrow x{\  \oplus}_{n}\ 1\}\)

For \(n = 3\), this means
\(t = \{ 0 \rightarrow 1,1 \rightarrow 2,2 \rightarrow 0\} = [ 1,2,0]\).
Since the range is the set of values produced by the formula (and so
implied by the formula), a concise version is
\(t = \{ x:Z_{n} \rightarrow x \oplus 1\}\), or
\(t(x:Z_{n}) = x \oplus 1\). If the domain is understood as well, then
simply \(t = \{ x \rightarrow x \oplus 1\}\) or \(t(x) = x \oplus 1\).

\hypertarget{compose}{%
\section{Compose}\label{compose}}

Functions can be composed. If \(a\) maps \(x \rightarrow y\) and \(b\)
maps \(y \rightarrow z\), then the composition \(c = b \circ a\) maps
\(x \rightarrow z\).

\(b \circ a:\ \{\)subdomain of \(a\} \rightarrow \{\)subrange of
\(b\} = \{ x \rightarrow b(a(x))\}\)

For example (using the ``list is also a function'' idea)

\begin{quote}
\([ 2,1,0] \circ [ 1,2,0] = \{ 0 \rightarrow 1 \rightarrow 1,1 \rightarrow 2 \rightarrow 0,2 \rightarrow 0 \rightarrow 2\} = \{ 0 \rightarrow 1,1 \rightarrow 0,2 \rightarrow 2\} = [ 1,0,2]\)
\end{quote}

The subdomain of \(a\) means some values \(x\) of the original domain of
\(a\) may not survive, because they may map to a value that is not in
the domain of \(b\). Similarly subrange of \(b\) means some values of
the original domain of \(b\) may never be part of the range of \(a\),
which may limit what the composed function maps to.

For example, let

\(a:\{ x:R \neq 0\} \rightarrow \{ y:R \neq 1\} = \{ x \rightarrow y = 1 + 1/x\}\),
and

\(b:\{ y:R \neq 0\} \rightarrow \{ z:R > 0\} = {\{ y \rightarrow z = 2}^{1/y}\}\)

Because \(a\) maps \(- 1\) to \(0\), and this is not an allowed input to
\(b\), it is not in the domain of \(a \circ b\), and because \(1\) is
never an output of \(a\), the value of \(b(1) = 2\) is not in the range
of \(a \circ b\) unless that value is mapped to for some other input (it
is not), so

\(a \circ b:\{ x:R\ \&\ x \neq 0\ \&\ x\  \neq - 1\} \rightarrow \{ z:R\ \&\ z > 0\ \&\ z \neq 2\} = \{ x \rightarrow {z = 2}^{1/(1 + 1/x)}\}\ \)

\hypertarget{multiple-arguments}{%
\section{Multiple Arguments}\label{multiple-arguments}}

\(m = \{[ x:R,y:R] \rightarrow [ x + y,x - y,x \times y,x \div y]\}\)
is a perfectly good function that takes a list of 2 real numbers, and
results in a list of 4 real numbers. Instead of
\(m([ 1,2]) = [ 3, - 1,2,1/2]\), we usually just
write \(m(1,2) = [ 3, - 1,2,1/2]\), or generically define
\(m\) by

\(m(x:R,y:R) = [ x + y,x - y,x \times y,x \div y]\)

\hypertarget{convex-function}{%
\section{Convex Function}\label{convex-function}}

For a real-valued function \(f\), saying \(f\) is convex means

\(f(px + qy + rz + \cdot \cdot \cdot ) \leq pf(x) + qf(y) + rf(z) + \cdot \cdot \cdot\)

for any values \(x\), \(y\), \(z\), \ldots{} in the domain of \(f\) and
any non-negative values \(p\), \(q\), \(r\), \ldots{} that sum to \(1\):
\(p + q + r + \cdot \cdot \cdot = 1\)

A result from calculus is any twice-differentiable function of a single
variable is convex if and only if its second derivative is nonnegative
on its entire domain. The negative of a convex function is concave and
vice versa.

\(f(x) = b^{x}\) for \(b > 0\) and \(f(x) = x^{\alpha}\) for
\(\alpha \geq 1\) are important convex functions here.

\hypertarget{concave-function}{%
\section{Concave Function}\label{concave-function}}

For a real-valued function \(f\), saying \(f\) is concave means

\(f(px + qy + rz + \cdot \cdot \cdot ) \geq pf(x) + qf(y) + rf(z) + \cdot \cdot \cdot\)

for any values \(x\), \(y\), \(z\), \ldots{} in the domain of \(f\) and
any non-negative values \(p\), \(q\), \(r\), \ldots{} that sum to \(1\):
\(p + q + r + \cdot \cdot \cdot = 1\)

A result from calculus is any twice-differentiable function of a single
variable is concave if and only if its second derivative is nonpositive
on its entire domain. The negative of a concave function is convex and
vice versa.

\(f(x) = log_{b}(x)\) for \(b > 1\) is an important concave function
here.

\hypertarget{logarithms-and-exponents}{%
\chapter{Logarithms and Exponents}\label{logarithms-and-exponents}}

When working with large numbers, logarithms represent large numbers with
smaller ones, they are connected by

\(log_{b}(n) = p\) (log form) is the same as \(n = b^{p}\) (exponent
form)

Here \(n\) is any positive number, \(b\) is a positive base, and \(p\)
is the power, which may be positive, negative, or zero. The most common
bases \(b\) are \(10\) in engineering, \(2\) in computer science, and
\(e \approx 2.718...\) in mathematics.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Logarithms roughly ``count digits'' in the given base. For example
  \(log_{10}(1\_ 000) = 3\) and \(log_{10}(1\_ 000\_ 000) = 6\). Writing
  \(32\) in binary is \(10\_ 0000_{2}\) and \(log_{2}(32) = 5\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Increasing a value by a factor of \(b\) increases the base \(b\)
  logarithm by \(1\): \(log_{b}(x \times b) = log_{b}(x) + 1\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Decreasing a value by a factor of \(b\) decreases the base \(b\)
  logarithm by \(1\): \(log_{b}(x \div b) = log_{b}(x) - 1\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Logarithms convert multiplication into addition:
  \(log_{b}(x \times y) = log_{b}(x) + log_{b}(y)\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Logarithms convert division into subtraction:
  \(log_{b}(x \div y) = log_{b}(x) - log_{b}(y)\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Logarithms convert powers into products:
  \(log_{b}(x^{y}) = y \times log_{b}(x)\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  For \(b > 1\), logarithms are concave functions:
  \(log_{b}(p \times x + q \times y) \geq p \times log_{b}(x) + q \times log_{b}(y)\)
  so long as \(x > 0\), \(y > 0\). \(p \geq 0\), \(q \geq 0\), and
  \(p + q = 1\). This can be extended to any number of terms.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  For \(b > 0\), exponents are convex functions:
  \(b^{p \times x + q \times y} \leq p \times b^{x} + q \times b^{y}\)
  so long as \(p \geq 0\), \(q \geq 0\), and \(p + q = 1\). This can be
  extended to any number of terms.
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{logic}{%
\chapter{Logic}\label{logic}}

Logic is a precise notation for making statements and following a chain
of reasoning. Instead of adopting mathematical notations for these, we
use a C-like convention which is much easier to remember and translate
into code.

\hypertarget{logic-not}{%
\section{Logic not (!)}\label{logic-not}}

Logic not \((!p)\) is true only when \(p\) is false.

If \(l\) is a list of logical statements,
\([!](l) = [!l(0),!l(1),...]\)

\hypertarget{logic-and}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Logic and
(\(\&\))}{Logic and (\textbackslash\&)}}\label{logic-and}}

Logic and \((p\ \&\ q\ \&\  \cdot \cdot \cdot )\) is true only when all
the statements \(p\), \(q\), \ldots{} are true.

If \(l\) is a list of logical statements
\([\&](l) = (l(0)\ \&\ l(1)\ \&\  \cdot \cdot \cdot )\)

\hypertarget{logic-or}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Logic or
(\(|\))}{Logic or (\textbar)}}\label{logic-or}}

Logic or \((p\ |\ q\ |\  \cdot \cdot \cdot )\) is false only when all
the statements \(p\), \(q\), \ldots{} are false.

If \(l\) is a list of logical statements
\([|](l) = (l(0)\ |\ l(1)\ |\  \cdot \cdot \cdot )\)

\hypertarget{logic-if-then-rightarrow}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Logic if-then
(\(\Rightarrow )\)}{Logic if-then (\textbackslash Rightarrow )}}\label{logic-if-then-rightarrow}}

Logic if-then (\(p \Rightarrow q)\) is a test of the logic of ``if
\(p\), then \(q\)''. This is a logical error only when \(p\) is true and
\(q\) is false. The \(\Rightarrow\) right associates, so
\(p \Rightarrow q \Rightarrow r \Rightarrow s\) means
\(p \Rightarrow (q \Rightarrow (r \Rightarrow s)).\)

If \(l\) is a list of logical statements
\([ \Rightarrow ](l) = (l(0)\  \Rightarrow \ l(1)\  \Rightarrow \cdot \cdot \cdot )\)

\hypertarget{repetition}{%
\chapter{Repetition}\label{repetition}}

Formulas can require repeated actions, we use several notations to
convey this.

\hypertarget{patterns}{%
\section{Patterns}\label{patterns}}

Patterns are an imprecise but typically adequate way of conveying a
repeated action. For example,
\(S = (0)^{2} + (1)^{2} + \cdot \cdot \cdot + (n - 1)^{2}\) means to sum
the squares of the elements of \(Z_{n}\), taken as \(S = 0\) when
\(n = 0\).

\hypertarget{sums}{%
\section{Sums}\label{sums}}

A precise notation for the same is
\(S = [ + ](\{ z:Z_{n} \rightarrow z^{2}\})\) The idea is
\([ + ]\) is a function that takes a function as an
argument. \([ + ]\) takes every input element of the domain
of the function provided, determines the corresponding output element of
the range, and adds the results together. If the domain is the empty
set, then we define \([ + ](\Theta) = 0\).

For example
\([ + ](\{ z:Z_{4} \rightarrow 2z + 1\}) = 1 + 3 + 5 + 7 = 16\)
and \([ + ](\{ z:Z_{0} \rightarrow 2z + 1\}) = 0\)

A common notation is \(\Sigma_x f(x) = [ + ](f)\).

If \(X\) is a subset of the domain of \(f\), then
\(\Sigma_{x \in X} f(x) = [ + ](\{ x:X \rightarrow f(x)\}) = [ + ](f(x:X))\)

\hypertarget{products}{%
\section{Products}\label{products}}

\([ \times ]\) is similarly defined, except the mapped
elements are multiplied, and we define
\([ \times ](\Theta) = 1\).

For example
\([ \times ](\{ z:Z_{4} \rightarrow 2z + 1\} = 1 \times 3 \times 5 \times 7 = 105\)
and \([ \times ](\{ z:Z_{0} \rightarrow 2z + 1\}) = 1\)

A common notation is \( \Pi_x f(x) = [ \times ](f)\), and similarly \( \Pi_{x \in X} f(x) = [ \times ](f(x:X))\)

\hypertarget{summation-rules}{%
\section{Summation Rules}\label{summation-rules}}

Generalizing
\(\left[ a \times y_{0} + b \times z_{0} \right] + \left[ a \times y_{1} + b \times z_{1} \right] = a \times (y_{0} + y_{1}) + b \times (z_{0} + z_{1})\),

\(\left[ af(x) + bg(x) \right] = af(x) + bg(x)\)

\([ + ](a \times f + b \times g) = a \times [ + ](f) + b \times [ + ](g)\)

From the Venn diagram,

\(f(x) = f(x) + f(x) - f(x)\)

\([ + ](f(x:X \cup Y)) = [ + ](f(x:X)) + [ + ](f(x:Y)) - [ + ](f(x:X \cap Y))\)

Because order does not matter when you are adding up terms,

\(\left[ f(x,y) \right] = \left[ f(x,y) \right] = f(x,y)\)

\([ + ](\{ x:X \rightarrow [ + ](f(x,y:Y))\}) = [ + ](\{ y:Y \rightarrow [ + ](f(x:X,y)))\}) = [ + ](f(x:X,y:Y))\)

Generalizing
\((y_{0} + y_{1})^{2} = y_{0} \times y_{0} + y_{0} \times y_{1} + y_{1} \times y_{0} + y_{1} \times y_{1}\),

\(\left[ f(x) \right]^{2} = \left[ f(x) \times f(x') \right]\)

\(\left[ [ + ](f(x:X)) \right]^{2} = [ + ](f(x:X) \times f(x':X))\)

\hypertarget{summation-formulas}{%
\section{Summation Formulas}\label{summation-formulas}}

By counting on your fingers,

\(1 = [ + ]\{ x:X \rightarrow 1\} = 1 + 1 + \cdot \cdot \cdot + 1 = \# X\)

By reversing the list and adding again,

\(z = [ + ]\{ z:Z_{n} \rightarrow z\} = 0 + 1 + \cdot \cdot \cdot + (n - 1) = \frac{n \times (n - 1)}{2}\)

By multiplying by \(\frac{b - 1}{b - 1}\) and canceling terms,

\(b^{z} = {[ + ]\{ z:Z_{n} \rightarrow b^{z}\} = b}^{0} + b^{1} + \cdot \cdot \cdot + b^{n - 1} = \frac{b^{n} - 1}{b - 1}\)

\hypertarget{summation-inequalities}{%
\section{Summation Inequalities}\label{summation-inequalities}}

\(l_{p}\)-norm

We define
\(\left| |f| \right|_{p} = \left\{ [ + ](|f|^{p}) \right\}^{1/p}\)
for \(p:R \geq 1\), and
\(\left| |f| \right|_{\infty} = [ max]\ |f(x)|\). (largest
absolute value in the range). These are called the \(l_{p}\)-norms and
for \(1 \leq p \leq \infty\) have the properties of a norm, which means,
for any finite domain real-valued functions \(f(x:X) \subseteq R\),
\(g(x:X) \subseteq R\), \(h(x:X) \subseteq R\), and real value \(c\):

\(\left| |cf| \right|_{p} = |c|\left| |f| \right|_{p}\)

\(\left| |f + g| \right|_{p} \leq \left| |f| \right|_{p} + \left| |g| \right|_{p}\)

\(\left| |f - g| \right|_{p} \leq \left| |f - h| \right|_{p} + \left| |h - g| \right|_{p}\)

\hypertarget{huxf6lders-inequality}{%
\subsection{Hölder's Inequality}\label{huxf6lders-inequality}}

If \(p:R > 1\), \(q:R > 1\), and \(1/p + 1/q = 1\), then
\(\left| |fg| \right|_{1} \leq \left| |f| \right|_{p}\left| |g| \right|_{q}\)

\hypertarget{counting}{%
\chapter{Counting}\label{counting}}

\hypertarget{decision-trees}{%
\section{Decision Trees}\label{decision-trees}}

Suppose an outcome is arrived from \(n\) decisions, with
\(c(0),c(1), \cdot \cdot \cdot ,c(n - 1)\) choices at each step.
Multiply all these factors together
\(c(0) \times c(1) \times \cdot \cdot \cdot \times c(n - 1) = [ \times ](c)\)

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(\#\{ outcomes\} \leq [ \times ](c)\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  If each outcome is unique, then
  \(\#\{ outcomes\} = [ \times ](c)\).
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

For example, tossing a coin (\(c(0) = 2\)), followed by a six-sided dice
(\(c(1) = 6\)) has
\([ \times ](c) = c(0) \times c(1) = 2 \times 6 = 12\)
outcomes (each choice leads to a unique outcome). This can be visualized
as a decision tree, where the initial branch is the choice of face on
coin, followed by the choice of pips on die.

\hypertarget{factorial}{%
\section{Factorial}\label{factorial}}

If you have \(n\) distinct things, there are
\(n! = n \times (n - 1) \times (n - 2) \times \cdot \cdot \cdot \times 1\)
ways to arrange them. This comes from the decisions tree, because you
have \(c_{0} = n\) choices for the initial element, then
\(c_{1} = n - 1\) for the next, etc.

This is exactly the situation for choosing arrangements of \(Z_{n}\), so
\(\# S_{n} = n!\)

\hypertarget{permutations}{%
\section{Permutations}\label{permutations}}

If you have \(n\ \)things and choose \(k \leq n\) of them, then you only
have the first \(k\) choices of the factorial idea. You can divide out
the extra factors of the formula to get just the product of the largest
\(k\) factors: \(\)

\(P(n,k) = \#\{\)\(n\) things taken \(k\) at a time, where order does
matter\(\} = \frac{n!}{(n - k)!}\)

\hypertarget{combinations}{%
\section{Combinations}\label{combinations}}

If order does not matter, then you can start by counting all of them as
if order did matter (permutations) and then divide by the number of ways
you can rearrange \(k\) things:

\(C(n,k) = \#\{\)\(n\) things taken \(k\) at a time, where order does
not matter\(\} = \frac{n!}{(n - k)! \times k!}\)

\hypertarget{groups}{%
\section{Groups}\label{groups}}

Groups are sets with an action we call compose \(\circ\) that takes two
(not necessarily different) elements and produces a third (not
necessarily different) element:

\(z = x \circ y\)

It does not have to be the traditional multiply (it will not be here).
Here are the main properties of groups.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  The action \(\circ\) does not depend on order parenthesis:
  \((x \circ y) \circ z = x \circ (y \circ z)\), so we can just as well
  write \(x \circ y \circ z\) because the result is the same regardless
  of how the factors are grouped. This works for any number of factors.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  There is a unique element \(e\) that does not change any of the values
  when composed with any group element: \(e \circ x = x \circ e = x\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Every element \(x\) has a unique (not necessarily different) element
  \(x^{- 1}\) which, when composed in either order, produces \(e\):
  \(x \circ x^{- 1} = x^{- 1} \circ x = e\). By the previous property,
  \(e^{- 1} = e\).
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

A familiar group would be all positive numbers (not just integers) with
the usual multiply for composition \(\circ = \times\) and \(e = 1\). If
you look at the list or requirements above you will see they are all
satisfied.

An important property of a finite group is that composition permutes all
the elements. Fix either side, say the left and think about the function
\(l_{a}:G \rightarrow G = \{ x \rightarrow y = a \circ x\}\). Because of
the inverse property of the group, \(y = a \circ x\) means
\(x = a^{- 1} \circ y\) so
\({l_{a}}^{- 1}:G \rightarrow G = \{ y \rightarrow {x = a}^{- 1} \circ y\}\)
is the inverse function for \(l_{a}\). Since \(G\) is finite and
\(l_{a}\) is an invertible function, this is the definition of a
permutation. The same argument works for
\(r_{a}:G \rightarrow G = \{ x \rightarrow y = x \circ a\}\). So
\(r_{a}\) and \(l_{a}\) are permutations for any group element \(a\).

\hypertarget{symmetric-group}{%
\section{Symmetric Group}\label{symmetric-group}}

In the sets section, we noted \(S_{n}\) is the set of all arrangements
of \(Z_{n} = \{ 0,1,2,...,n - 1\}\), and noted in the counting section
that there are \(\# S_{n} = n!\) elements this set. For example

\(S_{3} = \{[ 0,1,2],[ 0,2,1],[ 1,0,2],[ 1,2,0],[ 2,0,1],[ 2,1,0]\}\).

Here is a composition rule \(\circ\) for two permutations: if \(x\) and
\(y\) are permutations, we can make a permutation \(z = x \circ y\) by
selecting the values of \(y\) in the order of \(x\). So you are using
\(x\) to shuffle \(y\). For example,
\([ 2,0,1] \circ [ 1,2,0] = [ 0,1,2]\),
because the first permutation arranges the second in the order last,
initial, middle. This is also consistent with the ``list as a function''
idea and functional composition

\([ 2,0,1] \circ [ 1,2,0]\)

\(\{ 0 \rightarrow 2,1 \rightarrow 0,2 \rightarrow 1\} \circ \{ 0 \rightarrow 1,1 \rightarrow 2,2 \rightarrow 0\}\)

\(\{ 0 \rightarrow 1 \rightarrow 0,1 \rightarrow 2 \rightarrow 1,2 \rightarrow 0 \rightarrow 2\}\)

\(\{ 0 \rightarrow 0,1 \rightarrow 1,2 \rightarrow 2\}\)

\([ 0,1,2]\)

\(S_{n}\) under this composition rule is a group with

\(e = [ 0,1,2,...,n - 1]\),

and

\(x^{- 1} = [\)index of \(0\) in \(x\), index of \(1\) in
\(x\),..,index of \(n - 1\) in \(x\)\(]\).

\hypertarget{subgroup}{%
\section{Subgroup}\label{subgroup}}

A subgroup is itself a group but the elements are a subset of some
group.

A familiar subgroup using normal multiply as composition is the set of
reduced fractions \(p/q\) where \(p\) and \(q\) are positive integers
with no common factors; these are the positive fractions. Positive
fractions are a subgroup of all positive numbers under normal multiply.

\hypertarget{cyclic-subgroup}{%
\chapter{Cyclic Subgroup}\label{cyclic-subgroup}}

If you choose any element \(g\) of a finite group \(G\), then define
\(g^{0} = e\), \(g^{1} = g\), \(g^{n}\) for some positive integer \(n\)
as \(n\) repeated compositions of \(g\), and \(g^{- n}\) as \(n\)
compositions of \(g^{- 1}\). Since \(G\) is finite \(g^{n}\) must
eventually repeat, so there are \(m > n\) for which \(g^{n} = g^{m}\)
but multiplying by \(g^{- n}\) we see \(e = g^{m - n}\). Pick the
smallest \(l = m - n > 0\) for which this is true. If \(l = 1\) then you
chose \(g = e\). Otherwise write \(e = g^{l - 1} \circ g\) and so
\(g^{l - 1} = g^{- 1}\) (notice this also works in the \(l = 1\) case).
So \(g^{- n} = g^{n \times (l - 1)}\), and any power \(p\) can be
grouped into multiples \(k\) of \(l\) plus some number \(p_{0}\) in the
range \(0 \leq p_{0} < l\). By grouping terms we get
\(g^{p} = g^{kl + p_{0}} = (g^{l})^{k}g^{p_{0}} = e^{k}g^{p_{0}} = g^{p_{0}}\).
So powers of \(g\) form a cyclic subgroup of \(l\) elements.

They have the nice property \(g^{p + q} = g^{p{\  \oplus}_{l}\ q}\) for
any integer powers \(p\) and \(q\) and \(+\) is the usual addition and
\(\oplus_{l}\) is the modulo \(l\) addition.

\hypertarget{lagranges-theorem}{%
\section{Lagrange's Theorem}\label{lagranges-theorem}}

If \(S\) is a subgroup of a finite group \(G\), then \(\# G\) is a
multiple of \(\# S\).

Define \(gS\) as the set of elements produced by composing g with every
element of \(S\): \(gS = \{ gs\ |\ s\ \epsilon\ S\}\). Then
\(P = \{\ gS\ |\ g\ \epsilon\ G\ \}\) forms a partition of \(G\) (we
will show this in a moment). Since \(\# gS = \# S\), then we can count
the elements of \(G\) as \(\# G = \# P \times \# S\).

To show \(P\) is a partition, the subsets have to all be the same or
distinct (clearly their union is \(G\)). Suppose \(a\epsilon gS\) so and
\(a = gs_{0}\) But \(aS = \{ gs_{0}s|s\epsilon S\}\) but that's just a
permutation of \(gS\), so \(aS = gS\). So if any two elements of \(P\)
(like \(gS\) and \(g'S\)) have any element \(a\) in common, they are the
same set \(aS\).

\hypertarget{translation-subgroup}{%
\section{Translation Subgroup}\label{translation-subgroup}}

In the permutation group \(S_{n}\) an important subgroup is \(T_{n}\)
which are all the circular translations. It is generated by
\(t = [ 1,2,3,...,n - 2,n - 1,0]\). The other elements are

\(t^{0} = e = [ 0,1,2,3,...,n - 2,n - 1]\),

\(t^{1} = [ 1,2,3,...,n - 2,n - 1,0]\),

\(t^{2} = [ 2,3,...,n - 2,n - 1,0,1]\).

\(t^{n - 1} = [ n - 1,0,1,2,3,...,n - 2]\).

For example,
\(T_{3} = \{[ 0,1,2],[ 1,2,0],[ 2,1,0]\}\).

The translation group has the nice property
\(t^{x} \circ t^{y} = t^{x \oplus y}\).

\hypertarget{graph}{%
\chapter{Graph}\label{graph}}

A graph is a set of elements \(V\) called vertices connected by directed
edges \(E\), as in

Here \(V = Z_{3} = \{ 0,1,2\}\) and
\(E = \{ 1 \rightarrow 0,1 \rightarrow 2,2 \rightarrow 2\}\). \(E\) is
the ``connects to'' relationship for the \textbar graph.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  We call \(V(G)\) the set of all vertices of a graph \(G\), and
  \(E(G)\) the set of all edges.
  \end{quote}

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \begin{quote}
    For this tiny example, \(V(G) = \{ 0,1,2\}\), and
    \end{quote}
  \item
    \begin{quote}
    \(E(G) = \{ 1 \rightarrow 0,1 \rightarrow 2,2 \rightarrow 2\}\).
    \end{quote}
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  We define \(n(x)\) as the neighbors of \(x\), or
  \(\left\{ y\ |\ x \rightarrow y \right\}\) all the vertices \(y\)
  directly connected to \(x\).
  \end{quote}

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    \begin{quote}
    \(n(0) = \{\}\), \(n(1) = \{ 0,2\}\), and \(n(2) = \{ 0,2\}\) in the
    tiny example.
    \end{quote}
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{subgraph}{%
\section{Subgraph}\label{subgraph}}

A subgraph is itself a graph, but where the vertices and edges are a
subset of some graph's vertices and edges.

\hypertarget{induced-subgraph}{%
\section{Induced Subgraph}\label{induced-subgraph}}

An induced subgraph \(G[ S]\) for some subset
\(S \subseteq V(G)\) is the graph of with all the edges in \(E(G)\) that
start and end in \(S\): \(V(G[ S]) = S\),
\(E(G[ S]) = \{ x \rightarrow y\ in\ E(G)\ |\ x\ in\ S\ and\ y\ in\ S\}\).

\hypertarget{path}{%
\section{Path}\label{path}}

A path is a sequence of allowed edges, for example
\(1 \rightarrow 2 \rightarrow 2 \rightarrow 0\) above, and the length of
a path is the number of steps (3 in this example).

\hypertarget{tree-rooted-at-vertex-v}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Tree rooted at vertex
\(v\)}{Tree rooted at vertex v}}\label{tree-rooted-at-vertex-v}}

A graph is a tree rooted at vertex \(v\) if there is a unique path
starting from \(v\) to every other vertex.

\hypertarget{distance}{%
\section{Distance}\label{distance}}

The distance \(dist(start,end)\) between two vertices is the number of
steps (edges) of the shortest path from the start vertex to the end
vertex. This distance \(0\) if the two vertices are the same, and
\(\infty\) if there is no path that connects them. Notice that distance
does not have to be the same in both directions (because of one-way
roads, getting somewhere can be different than getting back). In the
above graph, \(dist(1,0) = 1\), but \(dist(0,1) = \infty\).

\hypertarget{ball}{%
\section{Ball}\label{ball}}

The open ball of size \(r\) around vertex \(v\), \(B_{r}(v)\) is the set
of all vertices that are a distance less than \(r\) from the start
\(v\). So for the example \(B_{0}(v) = \{\}\), \(B_{1}(v) = \{ v\}\),
\(B_{2}(0) = \{ 0\}\), \(B_{2}(1) = \{ 0,1,2\}\), and
\(B_{2}(2) = \{ 0,2\}\). We define \(B_{\infty}(v)\) as all the vertices
that have a finite path from \(v\) to them. For a finite graph, any
shortest path will visit at most every vertex, so
\(B_{\infty}(v) = B_{\# V}(v)\), so \(B_{3}\) is \(B_{\infty}\) in the
example.

\hypertarget{root-ball-size}{%
\section{Root Ball Size}\label{root-ball-size}}

For each vertex, the root ball size \(R(v)\) is the largest value of
\(r\) for which the induced subgraph \({G[ B}_{r}(v)]\) is a
tree rooted at \(v\).

\hypertarget{vertex-invariance}{%
\section{Vertex Invariance}\label{vertex-invariance}}

A vertex invariant graph looks the same from every vertex. A way to say
this that for every pair of vertices \(v\) and \(w\), there is at least
one re-labeling (permutation) of vertices where \(w \rightarrow v\) and
the edges are identical to the original graph.

\hypertarget{probability}{%
\chapter{Probability}\label{probability}}

A finite/countable probability space is a finite/countable set of
possible outcomes \(x\) in \(X\) and a non-negative number associated
with each outcome \(p(x)\), so that the sum of all probabilities equals
\(1\). The probability \(p(x)\) of an outcome \(x\) is the fraction of
times \(x\) is observed compared to some other result as the number of
independent trials get larger and larger.

\hypertarget{uniform-probability}{%
\section{Uniform Probability}\label{uniform-probability}}

Fair coins and fair dice have equal probability for every outcome. Since
the total probability is \(1\), \(p(x) = 1/\# X\). For example a fair
coin has \(p(H) = 1/2\) and \(p(T) = 1/2\).

\hypertarget{von-neumann-whitening}{%
\subsection{Von Neumann Whitening}\label{von-neumann-whitening}}

To create a fair coin from an unfair coin, toss any coin and group the
results in pairs. Delete all \([ H,H]\) and
\([ T,T]\) pairs, and replace \([ H,T]\) with
\(T\) and \([ T,H]\) with \(H\). The probability of heads in
the new sequence is
\(q(H) = \frac{p(T) \times p(H)}{p(T) \times P(H) + p(H) \times P(T)} = \frac{1}{2}\)
and similarly \(q(T) = \frac{1}{2}\).\\
Note that the pairs have to come from the same coin, but different pairs
can be from different coins to speed up the generation of random bits.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  procedure \(uniform!(Z_{2}) \rightarrow r:Z_{2}\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  repeat
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(t \leftarrow unfair!(Z_{2})\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(r \leftarrow unfair!(Z_{2})\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  until \(t \neq r\)
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

It is not a function in the mathematical sense, because the value it
produces changes each time it is used. We use \(uniform!(Z_{2})\) for
this because the action is a procedure that produces different results.

\hypertarget{perfect-binning}{%
\subsection{Perfect Binning}\label{perfect-binning}}

Suppose you have a base \(b\) uniform random number generator. How can
you create a uniform random number in \(Z_{n}\)? \(\)First choose the
smallest \(k\) so \(b^{k} \geq n\). Then write
\({\Delta = b}^{k}{\  \oplus}_{n}\ 0\).

Generate \(k\) random base \(b\) values, which can be thought of as an
unsigned number in the range \(0 \leq r < b^{k}\). If \(r\) is less than
\(\Delta\) then repeat this step.

The uniform value is \(r{\  \oplus}_{n}\ 0\).

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  procedure \(uniform!(Z_{n},b) \rightarrow r:Z_{n}\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(k \leftarrow ceil(log_{b}(n))\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(\Delta \leftarrow b^{k}{\  \oplus}_{n}\ 0\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  repeat
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(r \leftarrow 0\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  repeat \(k\) times
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(r \leftarrow b \times r + uniform!(Z_{b})\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  until last time
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  until \(r \geq \Delta\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(r \leftarrow r{\  \oplus}_{n}\ 0\)
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{uniformz_40}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\(uniform!(Z_{40})\)}{uniform!(Z\_\{40\})}}\label{uniformz_40}}

For \(n = 40\), it is useful to think of \(40\) as \(8 \times 5\). A
random \(3\) bit number perfectly bins the first factor. Then note that
for \(b = 2\), \(k = 4\), and \(n = 5\) in the perfect binning
algorithm, \(2^{4} = 3 \times 5 + 1\), so \(\Delta = 1\). So the second
factor only has to be re-generated \(1/16\) of the time, a fairly
efficient implementation is

\(uniform!(Z_{40}) = uniform!(Z_{8}) + 8 \times (uniform!(Z_{15}){\  \oplus}_{5}\ 0)\)

\hypertarget{uniforms_n}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\(uniform!(S_{n})\)}{uniform!(S\_\{n\})}}\label{uniforms_n}}

Let \([ i \leftrightarrow j]\) be the function that takes a
list and swaps index \(i\) and \(j\) of the list (this does nothing when
\(i = j\)). For example
\([ 0 \leftrightarrow 3]([\text{`a'},\text{`b'},\text{`c'},\text{`d'}]) = [\text{`d'},\text{`b'},\text{`c'},\text{`a'}]\).

The procedure is to randomly walk through the decision tree of choosing
the initial element, then the next, etc.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  procedure \(uniform!(S_{n}) \rightarrow r:S_{n}\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(r \leftarrow [ 0,1,...,n - 1]\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(m \leftarrow n\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  while \(m > 1\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(i \leftarrow uniform!(Z_{m})\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(r \leftarrow\)\([ m \leftrightarrow i](r)\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(m \leftarrow m - 1\)
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{shannon-information}{%
\section{Shannon Information}\label{shannon-information}}

The information (measured in bits) of a certain set \(X\ \)of outcomes
\(x\) with probabilities \(p(x)\) is the
\(H(p) = - p(x)\ log_{2}(p(x))\)

For uniform probabilities the information is \(log_{2}(\# X)\), which is
the largest it can be.

\hypertarget{missing-bits}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Missing Bits
}{Missing Bits }}\label{missing-bits}}

In security, it is preferable to have uniform distributions since that
provides the least amount of information to an attacker. So we define
\(p(x) = 1/\# X + \delta p(x)\). Substituting into the information
formula, \(M(p) = log_{2}(\# X) - H(p)\) is the number of missing bits
of information from non-uniformity of the probabilities. We can bound
\(M(p) \leq \frac{\# X}{log_{e}\ 2}(\delta p(x))^{2}\)

\(H(p) = - (1/\# X + \delta p(x))\ log_{2}(1/\# X + \delta p(x))\)

\(= - (1/\# X + \delta p(x))\ \left[ log_{2}(1/\# X) + log_{2}(1 + \# X\delta p(x)) \right]\)

\(= log_{2}(\# X) - \frac{1}{\# X}(1 + \# X\delta p(x))log_{2}(1 + \# X\delta p(x))\)

\(M(p) = log_{2}(\# X) - H = \frac{1}{\# X}(1 + \# X\delta p(x))log_{2}(1 + \# X\delta p(x))\)

Using \(log_{2}(x) = \frac{log_{e}(x)}{log_{e}(2)}\), and
\(log_{e}(1 + x) \leq x\)

\(M(p) \leq \frac{1}{\# Xlog_{e}2}(1 + \# X\delta p(x))\# X\delta p(x)\)

\(= \frac{\# X}{log_{e}2}(\delta p(x))^{2}\)

Missing Bits (Improved)

This can sharpened by restricting \(X\) to eliminate where the
probability is known to be zero. Let \(X'\) be a subset of \(X\) where
\(p(x) = 0\) outside of \(X'\). The above estimate is correct in the
restricted domain \(X'\) and for the whole space \(X\) we obtain
\(log_{2}(\# X') - M'(p) \leq H(p) \leq log_{2}(\# X')\) where

\(M'(p) \leq \frac{\# X'}{log_{e}2}(p(x) - 1/\# X')^{2}\).

\hypertarget{lower-bounds}{%
\section{Lower Bounds}\label{lower-bounds}}

We show
\(- \frac{\alpha}{\alpha - 1}log_{2}\left| |p| \right|_{\alpha} \leq H(p)\)
for \(\alpha > 1\).

From concavity of the logarithm function

\(log_{2}p(x)f(x) \geq p(x)log_{2}(f(x))\)

Choosing

\(f(x) = (p(x))^{\alpha - 1}\), \(\alpha > 1\)

Gives

\(log_{2}(p(x))^{\alpha} \geq (\alpha - 1)p(x)log_{2}(p(x))\)

Or

\(- \frac{\alpha}{\alpha - 1}log_{2}\left[ (p(x))^{\alpha} \right]^{1/\alpha} \leq - p(x)log_{2}(p(x))\)

Or

\(- \frac{\alpha}{\alpha - 1}log_{2}\left| |p| \right|_{\alpha} \leq H(p)\)

In the uniform case \(p(x) = 1/\# X\), this result is sharp,

\(\left| |p| \right|_{\alpha} = \left[ \# X(1/\# X)^{\alpha} \right]^{1/\alpha} = (\# X)^{1/\alpha - 1} = (\# X)^{- \frac{\alpha - 1}{\alpha}}\)

So
\(- \frac{\alpha}{\alpha - 1}log_{2}\left| |p| \right|_{\alpha} = H(p)\)

\hypertarget{entropy-of-product-in-group}{%
\section{Entropy of Product in
Group}\label{entropy-of-product-in-group}}

If \(p(x)\) and \(q(x)\ \) are probability distributions for elements of
a finite group \(G\), then the probability distribution for the product
is

\(r(z) = p(x)\ q(x^{- 1} \circ z)\)

Here we show

\(H(r) = - \left[ p(x)q(y)log_{2}(r(x \circ y)) \right]\)

Using the definition,

\(H(r) = - r(z) \times \ log_{2}(r(z))\)

In the first definition for \(r(z)\) we sum over \(x\) and the second we
sum over \(y\):

\(H(r) = - \left( p(x)\ q(x^{- 1} \circ z) \right) \times log_{2}\left( p(y)\ q(y^{- 1} \circ z) \right)\)

We can distribute the \(log_{2}\) factor into the \(x\)-sum, and then
switch summation order

\(H(r) = - \left[ p(x)q(x^{- 1} \circ z)log_{2}\left( p(y)\ q(y^{- 1} \circ z) \right) \right]\)

And changing variables in the sum on \(z\) with \(w\) with the
permutation \(x^{- 1} \circ z = w\),

\(H(r) = - \left[ p(x)q(w)log_{2}\left( p(y)\ q(y^{- 1} \circ x \circ w) \right) \right]\)

\(= - \left[ p(x)q(w)log_{2}(r(x \circ w)) \right]\)

Or, changing summation variables, we have our result

\(H(r) = - \left[ p(x)q(y)log_{2}(r(x \circ y)) \right]\)

\hypertarget{hr-leq-hp-hq}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\(H(r) \leq H(p) + H(q)\)}{H(r) \textbackslash leq H(p) + H(q)}}\label{hr-leq-hp-hq}}

\(r(x \circ y) = p(z)\ q(z^{- 1} \circ x \circ y)\)

We can instead sum over \(w\) with \(z = x \circ w\) or
\(w = x^{- 1} \circ z\), which is just a permutation of the sum, so

\(r(x \circ y) = p(x \circ w)\ q(w{}^{- 1} \circ y)\)

Now in the \(log_{2}\) of the sum, we can distinguish the \(w = e\)
term:

\(H(r) = - \left[ p(x)q(y)log_{2}\left( p(x)\ q(y) + p(x \circ w)\ q(w{}^{- 1} \circ y) \right) \right]\)

\(- log_{2}(u)\) is a decreasing function so dropping the remaining
terms can only increase it's value,

\(H(r) \leq - \left[ p(x)q(y)log_{2}\left( p(x)\ q(y) \right) \right]\)

\(= - \left[ p(x)q(y)[ log_{2}(p(x)) + log_{2}(q(y))] \right]\)

\(= H(p) + H(q)\)

\hypertarget{computation}{%
\chapter{Computation}\label{computation}}

Cryptography lies in an interesting boundary between mathematics and
computation. The goal in cryptography is to make practical algorithms
(functions that can be computed in a reasonable amount of time and a
high probability of success) that, without certain information usually
referred to as the key information, are impossible to compute.

So, to prove that a cryptographic idea is secure, you need to prove that
no human or machine can decipher it without the key information. Which
means you have to have some idea of how hard it is to compute something.
Which means you have to have some idea of what a computer is, or, at
least, what it can do.

\hypertarget{processor-model-of-computation}{%
\section{Processor Model of
Computation}\label{processor-model-of-computation}}

These are classical computers, where processing units do basic math and
logic steps according to instructions written in a program stored in
memory, and modify data also stored in memory which represents the
progress of computation. From a function point of view, the initial
configuration of memory is the input, and, once the processor reaches a
``finished'' state, the final configuration represents the output.

\hypertarget{neuron-model-of-computation}{%
\section{Neuron Model of
Computation}\label{neuron-model-of-computation}}

These mimic the structure of a biological brain, where a neuron behaves
according to the neurons they are connected to. As a computation model,
these are graphs where the value at each vertex at time \(t\) is a
function of the values of the vertices of all incoming edges at time
\(t - 1\), with some assigned (input) values at \(t = 0\).

These two models of computation represent essentially all non-biological
computation. From a complexity point of view, either one can be used to
mimic the other, so there is nothing foundationally better about either.
But there is another model of computation.

\hypertarget{probabilistic-model-of-computation}{%
\section{Probabilistic Model of
Computation}\label{probabilistic-model-of-computation}}

Instead of absolute logic steps like a processor based computer, such as
in ``if y is 3, then set x to 1'', a probabilistic processor allows
assignments like ``if y is 3, then set x 3 to with 90\% likelihood, and
set x to 7 with 10\% likelihood''. Using a large number of processor
based computers, the behavior of a probabilistic computer can be
simulated, and similarly a probabilistic neural computer can be
simulated with a large number of classical neural based computers.

The key is ``large number of classical computers'': a single
probabilistic computer can compute certain things much more efficiently
than a traditional processor or neural based computer. Cryptographers
are particularly nervous about this probabilistic pseudo-code:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  function crack(cipher,plain,keyset) \(\rightarrow\) key
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  test\_key \(\leftarrow\) every element of keyset (with equal
  probability)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  if decode(cipher,test\_key) = plain then
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  key \(\leftarrow\) test\_key
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  else
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  key \(\leftarrow\) 0
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

If an attacker possesses a probabilistic computer that can execute this
program efficiently, then the key can be quickly recovered. Because of
this potential power there is significant effort to create such a
computer.

This is an opinion. A useful probabilistic computer will be a state
secret, used only to crack very high value ciphers because revealing
such a tool would diminish its value to the possessor. If your secrets
are this important, then I am humbled by your interest in this cipher,
and suggest you should be careful indeed. We have a few theorems
regarding the safety of the cipher with regard to this kind of opponent.

We mostly work to defend against an attacker with a lot of traditional
computer resources and wants to run this kind of attack (a probabilistic
computer can do all cases at once, a normal computer has to try each
case separately):

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  function crack(cipher,plain,keyset) \(\rightarrow\) key
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  repeat
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  key \(\leftarrow\) next in keyset (in order of likelihood)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  until decode(cipher,test\_key) = plain
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

More correctly, this problem is broken up among many computers, each
searching a portion of the key space, so, if the attacker has
\(1\_ 000\_ 000\) computers, this can be done about \(1\_ 000\_ 000\)
times faster than one. Also, if there is a flaw in the design of the
cipher, it may be possible to extract the key or at least decode the
cipher with much less effort than finding the key.

Spider Cipher uses the arrangement of a 40 card deck as the key. So the
key space has

\hypertarget{approx-2159.159}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\(815\_ 915\_ 283\_ 247\_ 897\_ 734\_ 345\_ 611\_ 269\_ 596\_ 115\_ 894\_ 272\_ 000\_ 000\_ 000 \approx 2^{159.159}\)}{815\textbackslash\_ 915\textbackslash\_ 283\textbackslash\_ 247\textbackslash\_ 897\textbackslash\_ 734\textbackslash\_ 345\textbackslash\_ 611\textbackslash\_ 269\textbackslash\_ 596\textbackslash\_ 115\textbackslash\_ 894\textbackslash\_ 272\textbackslash\_ 000\textbackslash\_ 000\textbackslash\_ 000 \textbackslash approx 2\^{}\{159.159\}}}\label{approx-2159.159}}

elements. Here is a version of understanding how big this is

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  There are about \(10\_ 000\_ 000\_ 000\) (10 billion) people in the
  world.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  A person has about \(10\_ 000\_ 000\) (10 million) hairs on their
  body.
  \end{quote}
\end{itemize}

So, if each person had \(1\_ 000\_ 000\) (1 million) computers on every
hair of their body, and each of these computers were trying to crack
\(1\_ 000\_ 000\_ 000\) (1 billion) keys per second, then it would take
more than \(250\_ 000\_ 000\) (250 million) years to try all the keys.

\hypertarget{why-not-larger}{%
\section{Why not larger?}\label{why-not-larger}}

A key chosen at random from a set of \(2^{159}\) elements is profoundly
safe. Making the key space larger has no impact on security; since the
only plausible way to attack such a key space is to use a new technology
(probabilistic computer) or exploit some flaw in the cipher, or flaw in
the choice of key. Larger key spaces do not keep flaws from being
problematic, and only postpone the inevitable in the face of a
probabilistic computer.

\hypertarget{why-not-smaller}{%
\section{Why not smaller?}\label{why-not-smaller}}

This is so large that a smaller key also makes sense, but it is natural
to use \(40\) cards as a subset of a typical \(52\) card playing deck,
and the arithmetic is easier for humans with a simple modulus like
\(40\).

\hypertarget{probabilistic-automata}{%
\section{Probabilistic Automata}\label{probabilistic-automata}}

From the point of view of the manner in which the cipher traverses the
key space, a useful model is a Probabilistic Automata. In a
probabilistic automata, the state of the system is a probability
distribution \(p(x,t)\), which is the probability of the automata being
in the state \(x:X\) at time \(t\). From each state, according to the
input, there is a probability of transition to another state, so
\(T(\sigma,x,y)\) is the transition probability of transitioning from
state \(x\) to state \(y\) if the input to the automata is signal \(s\).
We insist that, for any choice of initial state \(x\) and signal \(s\),
the transition probability sum to \(1\): \(T(s,x,y) = 1\)

If \(s(t)\) is the signal over time, the state of the system evolves
according to some initial state distribution \(p(x,0) = p_{0}(x)\), and
then transitions according to

\(p(y,t + 1) = T(s(t),x,y)p(x,t)\)

If the signal is also a probability then we also sum over the signal set
\(S\) and provide a probability distribution, \(p_{s}(s,t)\), for the
signal at time \(t\),

\(p(y,t + 1) = p_{s}(s,t)T(s,x,y)p(x,t)\)

\hypertarget{spider-graph}{%
\chapter{Spider Graph}\label{spider-graph}}

The spider graph has vertices \(V = S_{40}\), the set of all
arrangements of \(Z_{40}\). For each vertex \(v\) there are \(40\)
outgoing edges,
\(\{ v \rightarrow s \circ t^{0} \circ v,v \rightarrow s \circ t^{1} \circ v,v \rightarrow s \circ t^{2} \circ v,...,v \rightarrow s{\circ t}^{39} \circ v\}\).
Here \(t^{c}\) are the members of \(T_{40}\), and {[}count down by odds,
then up by evens{]}

\(s = [ 39,37,35,33,31,...,9,7,5,3,1,0,2,4,6,8,...30,32,34,36,38]\).

This is the act of cutting the deck at index \(c\) followed by a
back-front shuffle.

From a user's point of view, the spider graph is a deterministic finite
automata. Picking a key is selecting an initial vertex, and encrypting
or decrypting is moving through the spider graph along edges.

From an attacker's point of view, the randomness of the initial key is
the initial probability distribution for the probabilistic automata. The
signal is the envelope, which contains the plain text and the padding.
The padding is purely random, while the plain text has various degrees
of information. From the attacker's point of view, the most information
is a known plaintext attack, where the plain text steps are
deterministic.

\hypertarget{spider-graph-is-vertex-invariant}{%
\section{Spider Graph is Vertex
Invariant}\label{spider-graph-is-vertex-invariant}}

To make vertex \(w\) look like vertex \(v\), relabel all the vertices
\(x\) by composing on the right by
\(x \rightarrow x \circ (w^{- 1} \circ v)\). This shifts the labels as
desired, and, by the same right multiplication, re-labels all the edges
as required.

This has several important consequences. First, from a security point of
view, the graph state is so uniform that no amount of observation of
movement through the graph can reveal any information about the starting
point (key). An analogy would be trying to figure out where you were on
a sphere by walking around - all you would know is the path you took but
without some external reference it reveals nothing about where you are
or where you started.

Second, the structure of the graph is equal everywhere, so properties of
the graph can be studied from any vertex. This reduces the computational
complexity of understanding the graph (but not the security of using it)
by \(\# S_{40} = 40!\)

\hypertarget{spider-graph-is-fully-connected}{%
\section{Spider Graph is Fully
Connected}\label{spider-graph-is-fully-connected}}

That means every vertex \(v\) can reach every other vertex thorough some
path: \(B_{\infty}(v) = S_{40}\). If \(v\) is some choice of initial
key, then working the cipher is moving through the spider graph which,
by definition, limits the active state space to \(B_{\infty}(v)\). If
this subgraph is smaller than the full graph, then the scheme is really
not as secure as \(40!\) states.

The proof cannot reasonably be done without some computer assistance.
Here are the steps.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Because of the vertex invariance we need only consider one point,
  \(e = [ 0,1,...,39]\). If \(B_{\infty}(e) = S_{40}\) then
  \(B_{\infty}(v) = S_{40}\) for every other vertex \(v\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Anything \(e\) reaches can be part of the path. Suppose
  \(e \rightarrow \cdot \cdot \cdot \rightarrow v\) by some path. This
  means
  \(v = (s \circ t^{c_{p - 1}}) \circ (s \circ t^{c_{p - 2}}) \circ \cdot \cdot \cdot \circ (s \circ t^{c_{0}})\),
  where \(p\) is the path length and
  \([ c_{0},c_{1},...,c_{p - 1}]\) is the sequence of cuts
  used along the path. So \(v\) is shorthand for this sequence of cuts
  that can be used in any path.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(e\) as a cycle, and \(s^{- 1}\). By choosing \(c = 0\)
  in the edge transition \(x \rightarrow s \circ t^{c} \circ x\) we can
  reach \(s^{k}\) for any \(k > 0\). Since \(S_{40}\) is finite this
  must eventually repeat a vertex \(s^{k_{0}} = s^{k_{1}}\). Multiplying
  by \(s^{- k_{0}}\) we see \(e = s^{k_{1} - k_{0}}\), which shows we
  can reach \(e\) as a cycle. By splitting one factor of \(s\) from
  this, we see \(e = s^{k_{1} - k_{0} - 1} \circ s\), which shows
  \(s^{- 1} = s^{k_{1} - k_{0} - 1}\), so \(s^{- 1}\) is reachable.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(T_{40}\). First reach \(s^{- 1}\), then move along the
  edge \(v \rightarrow t^{c} \circ s \circ v\), so
  \(s^{- 1} \rightarrow t^{c} \circ s \circ s^{- 1} = t^{c}\)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches everywhere the inverse spider graph reaches (where all
  the edges are reversed). The inverse graph uses the transitions
  \(v \rightarrow t^{40 - c} \circ s^{- 1} \circ v\), but we can reach
  these since we can reach \(s^{- 1}\) and all of \(T_{40}\).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(r = [ 39,38,37,...,2,1,0]\), the
  permutation that reverses the deck.
  \(r = s^{- 1}{\circ t}^{20} \circ s\). This is verifiable by hand but
  also done as a computer proof as FACTS(RReachable).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(x = [ 1,0,3,2,5,4,...,37,36,39,38]\) the
  permutation that swaps all pairs of the deck.
  \(x = s^{- 1} \circ r \circ s\), as demonstrated in FACTS(XReachable).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches
  \(b_{i,i \oplus 1} = [ 0,1,2,...,i \oplus 1,i,...,38,39]\)
  the permutation that swaps \(i\) with \(i \oplus 1\) in the deck
  (where \(\oplus\) is \(+\) modulo 40).
  \(b_{i,i \oplus 1} = t^{- (i \oplus 1)} \circ t^{39} \circ x \circ t \circ r \circ s^{- 1} \circ t^{21} \circ s \circ t^{i \oplus 1}\),
  as demonstrated in FACTS(BReachable).
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(b_{i,j}\) which swaps index \(i\) with index \(j\). We
  might as well assume \(i < j\). Since
  \(b_{i,j} = t^{- i}{\circ b}_{0,j - i} \circ t^{i}\), we might as well
  assume \(i = 0\). \(b_{0,1}\) has already been demonstrated as
  reachable. For \(j > 1\),
  \(b_{0,j} = b_{j - 1,j} \circ b_{0,j - 1} \circ b_{j - 1,j}\) . By
  induction any \(b_{0,j}\) is reachable and so \(b_{i,j}\) is reachable
  in general. This is demonstrated in FACTS(SReachable)
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  \(e\) reaches \(S_{40}\). Any permutation \(v\) can be sorted into
  \(e\) by a series of swaps. Applying the inverse of these swaps to
  \(e\) produces \(v\), so any \(v\) is reachable.
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{group-products-hold-entropy}{%
\chapter{Group Products Hold
Entropy}\label{group-products-hold-entropy}}

Let \(p(x)\) and \(q(x)\) be two probability distributions on the group
\(G\), then the distribution of the product is

\(r(x) = p(a)q(a^{- 1} \circ x)\)

Write \(p(x) = 1/\# G + \delta p(x)\) and
\(q(x) = 1/\# G + \delta q(x)\), then this simplifies to

\(r(x) = 1/\# G + \delta r(x)\), where
\(\delta r(x) = \delta p(a)\delta q(a^{- 1} \circ x)\),
\(E(\delta r) = 0\),
\(E(\delta r^{2}) = \delta p(a)\delta q(a^{- 1} \circ x)\delta p(b)\delta q(b^{- 1} \circ x)\)

