\hypertarget{mixing-near-saturation}{%
\chapter{Mixing Near Saturation}\label{mixing-near-saturation}}

The free depth governs entropy capture while the state is far from
uniform (the capture theorem is stated in the companion \emph{Perfect
Spider Cipher Theory}). Near saturation -- when the state entropy is
already close to \(log_{2}(40!)\) -- a different mechanism takes over,
and it applies equally to the plain and perfect spider: spectral
contraction. Write the deficit as
\(\epsilon_{k} = log_{2}(40!) - H(X_{k})\), and call the inputs blind
when the cut choices are independent of the state, as random padding
cards are.

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  The deficit never increases. Every step is a blind mixture of
  bijections of the state space, and such a mixture cannot move a
  distribution away from uniform.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  Any single card's position is exactly uniform after one blind card:
  the uniform cut already does it, before the shuffle acts at all.
  \end{quote}
\item
  \begin{quote}
  So the slowest statistics are pairs. A cut preserves the cyclic
  difference between two cards' positions, and pair statistics
  therefore evolve by the \emph{difference chain}

  \(K(d,d') = \frac{1}{40}\#\{ x:\pi(x + d) - \pi(x) = d'\}\)

  where \(\pi\) is the position map of one shuffle. This chain is the
  original design criterion -- after a shuffle, the distances between
  cards should look random -- in exact form. It is doubly stochastic,
  so its stationary distribution is uniform, and its contraction rate
  is the mixing rate of pair statistics.
  \end{quote}
\end{enumerate}

The long-run contraction rate of the difference chain, computed
numerically, is essentially the same for every variant: spectral
radius about \(0.43\) for plain spider, \(0.43\) for the perfect
shuffle, \(0.44\) for the rejected first/last swap. Each blind card
multiplies the pair-level \(\chi^{2}\) deficit by about \(0.19\):
about \(2.4\) bits of log-deficit per card, or \(1.2\) bits at the
standard-deviation level, consistent with the contraction estimated in
the previous chapter.

Two remarks. First, mixing is insensitive to the perfect swap: the
swap governs cycles and free depth, while the contraction rate belongs
to the cut-and-back-front structure both ciphers share. Each design
question has its own knob, and each was tuned by its own instrument.
Second, the pair level is computed, not proved extremal: higher-order
correlations are conjectured to mix no slower, as in other
card-shuffling chains, but the full spectral gap of either spider
graph is open.

Putting the regimes together, blind inputs give three simultaneous
lower bounds,

\(H(X_{k}) \geq max\left( H(X_{k - 1}),\ H(class(X_{0})) + k\, log_{2}40,\ log_{2}(40!) - \epsilon_{k} \right)\)

the first always, the second while \(k\) is within the class free
depth, the third with \(\epsilon_{k}\) contracting at the spectral
rate once the state is near uniform. The handoff between the second
and third arms happens near the birthday depth.

Finally, the same object that certifies capture also bounds mixing
from \emph{arbitrary} starting distributions. The collision mass
\(\left\| w^{\ast k} \right\|_{2}^{2}\) of the \(k\)-step word
distribution equals \(40^{- k}\) exactly while \(k\) is within the
free depth, and by Young's inequality every starting distribution
satisfies
\(\left\| p_{k} - u \right\|_{2} \leq 2\left\| w^{\ast k} \right\|_{2}\).
If the collision mass continues near \(40^{- k}\) to
\(k \approx 30\) -- the birthday estimate -- the whole graph mixes in
about thirty blind cards from any start, and the spectral rate above
scrubs whatever deficit remains. The certified free depth is the
proven prefix of that estimate; extending it is the open computational
frontier.

